node.accessibility_caption:
Some signs of work-life imbalance:
•You resent going to work or feel unappreciated there.
•You have become the go-to fixer and rescuer, even when you are scheduled to be off.
•Most of your conversations in and out of work are about your job.
•It feels like it has taken over your identity and life.
•Supportive loved ones express concern about burnout.

node.text:
There are times in your life when imbalance is inevitable and ok.
.
For me, grad school was years of the balance tipped over on the work side of things. I set realistic expectations for what I could accomplish toward taking care of myself. I got good at saying no, even when it made me less of a star student.
.

•Most of your conversations in and out of work are about your job.

node.accessibility_caption: Affordable Self-care: stop creating competitions that don’t matter.

node.text:
You know...the ones that stress you out for no good reason. It’s about saving our emotional energy for the battles that matter.
.
Let them get the parking spot.
Let them get the last word in a not very important argument.
.
Accept that they may get the higher test score, the better office, the nicer car.
.
Sometimes it’s us driving the competitive energy. Sometimes it’s someone else. Either way, you get to decide whether or not it is worth it to you to engage.
.
What are other not-worth-it competitions that people start?
.
caption [Affordable Self-care: stop creating competitions that don’t matter.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: life is feeling really messy and stressful. You are under no obligation to try to transform it into some great work of art.

node.text:
It’s ok if your greatest accomplishment right now is simply getting through the day.
.
It’s ok if you spend your time outside of work resting and recovering.
.
There are going to be people out there trying to sell the idea that this is your moment to dive deep into some huge creative or business venture. Maybe you feel ready for that. It’s ok if you don’t.
.
You don’t have to maximize your time at home writing the next big novel, learning an instrument, or teaching yourself a new language. It’s ok to opt out.
.
Caption [life is feeling really messy and stressful. You are under no obligation to try to transform it into some great work of art.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: So much of the work of relationship boundaries involves keeping the ones we set with ourselves.

node.text:
There are at least a half a million posts on Instagram by now talking all about how to set and maintain boundaries with others. I get it. Relationships are complicated and ever adapting. We struggle with them and need to learn skills to keep our relationships healthy.
.
And still, I think we miss something with all of our focusing on other people. We miss all of the opportunities we have to listen to our needs and honor our values within our relationship with ourself.
.
Though you can’t control the choices and decisions that other people make, you have a lot more say over the ways you choose to relate to yourself.
.
Caption [So much of the work of relationship boundaries involves keeping the ones we set with ourselves.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: Your body doesn’t have an on/off switch. It makes sense if you need some time to settle into a slower rhythm if you’ve spent a lot of time rushing around.

node.text:
What do you do to help settle your body down?
.
Here are some of my strategies:
1. Remind myself that it’s going to take some time…and that’s ok.
2. Drink a glass of water.
3. Take a walk to burn off energy.
4. Listen to slow music with a strong beat.
5. Focus on slowing and relaxing my breath.
6. Play the piano.
.
How about you?
.
@foglietto_fr notecards
.

node.accessibility_caption: just because it’s happening for them doesn’t mean it will never happen for you.

node.text:
Their timeline isn’t your deadline. It’s not fair to you, and it’s not fair to them to get stuck in the comparison trap.
.
Keep going.
.

.

node.accessibility_caption: Affordable Self-care: set more realistic expectations about how long things take to get done.

node.text:
Let’s call it optimism...or poor planning. I always think I will be able to get things done a lot faster than is realistic.
.
And what happens? I get impatient and frustrated. I get stressed or irritable. I end up running late. Others of us might get self-critical or shaming.
.
It’s actually fairly simple to avoid all of those negative feelings. It’s about setting more realistic expectations, goals, and timeframes.
.
And as a parent, it’s about learning that things always take longer with kids in tow...and that it’s not really a problem if we adapt to the situation instead of assuming that the situation will adapt to us.
.
caption [Affordable Self-care: set more realistic expectations about how long things take to get done.]

node.accessibility_caption: authenticity doesn’t mean you are an open book.

node.text:
You still get to have boundaries. You still get a say in what people know about you.
.
As a therapist, my goal is to be fully present and my most genuine self with my clients. Does that mean they must know the details of my life, my past? No way.
.
And you know what? The process is the better for it. They don’t get tripped up in worrying about my stuff and are better able to figure out their own.
.
Caption [authenticity doesn’t mean you are an open book.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: sometimes people do you a favor when they reject you.

node.text:
No one wins everyone over.
.
It sucks to get rejected...from jobs and schools...by people you want to date or be friends with. Trust me though. Sometimes it’s better to be rejected.
.
They might be seeing something you don’t that will get in the way later. Maybe they tells you they really want a long-term relationship (like you) when they really don’t. Or, that school can tell they aren’t a great fit. It’s better to be rejected early and shift to another plan, than it is to find out when those other options are gone.
.
Has this happened to you?
.
Caption [sometimes people do you a favor when they reject you.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: affordable self-care: keep a list of coping strategies and reminders that have been helpful to you.

node.text:
And keep them in a handy place.
.
What are helpful reminders and coping practices for you?
.
Here are some of mine:
1. Take a few slow, gentle breaths.
2. Drink a glass of water.
3. Walk or do some kind of exercise.
4. Talk to a friend or my husband.
5. Take a break.
6. Remind myself that this feeling won’t last forever.
.
Caption [affordable self-care: keep a list of coping strategies and reminders that have been helpful to you.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: Affordable Self-care: allow people to help you.

node.text:
Ok, so maybe not the people who attach manipulative strings to their help. Their help is often more trouble than it’s worth.
.
Accept the help that the rest of us offer.
.
•Let us open the door for you.
•Let people bring you food when you are sick.
•Let people do their share of the group project.
.
We undermine people’s efforts to help (and connect) when we reject their offers...or go back and correct what they have done. Just accept the help and move on.
.

.

node.text:

.
